# LICENSE — Dual-Track

This project (`perimeter`) is released under a **dual-track license** to
balance open research with anti-commercial-abuse protections, following the
common practice of academic + security-research projects (e.g., Trail of Bits
/ NCC Group / Project Zero companion repos).

## Track 1 — Code: AGPL-3.0-only

The following directories and files contain **executable code** and are
licensed under the **GNU Affero General Public License v3.0**. Full license
text: <https://www.gnu.org/licenses/agpl-3.0.txt> (SPDX: `AGPL-3.0-only`).

Covered paths:

- `revers/` — 9 pure-algorithm modules
- `stample/*/px_cookie/` — iFood + Grubhub generators
- `bundle/script/` — Bundle userscripts and shell helpers
- `bundle/stample/helpers/` — WASM extraction / mouse trajectory tools
- `node_bridge/` — Plan B environment-patching code
- `skill/*/scripts/` — All CLI scripts under any skill directory
- Any other `.js` / `.py` / `.sh` files inside the repository unless
  otherwise marked

SPDX identifier: `AGPL-3.0-only`

Key effect: **anyone who uses this code to run a network service (SaaS,
internal tool serving multiple users, hosted scraper, etc.) MUST publish
their complete corresponding source code under the same AGPL-3.0 license**.
Internal personal use, academic research, and security audit are all
permitted without copyleft obligation as long as the modified code is not
distributed or operated as a service for third parties.

## Track 2 — Documentation: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

The following content is **documentation, methodology, captures, and
research material** and is licensed under the **Creative Commons
Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International** license. Full
license text: <https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/legalcode>
(SPDX: `CC-BY-NC-SA-4.0`).

Covered paths:

- `main/` — All Chinese and English methodology, technical reference, and
  field documents
- `bug_report/` — All gotcha documents, drift cases, and worklogs
- `research/` — All six research dossiers
- `bundle/doc/` — Bundle full technical documentation
- `bundle/source/SDK_INFO.md`, `bundle/source/WASM_ANALYSIS.md` — Bundle
  metadata and WASM analysis docs
- All `README.md`, `README_EN.md`, `SKILL.md`, and similar narrative files
  anywhere in the repository
- `stample/*/sample/` — Real-capture sample metadata and decoded JSON
  references (but not the underlying captured byte streams, which are
  ephemeral protocol data and not authored content)

SPDX identifier: `CC-BY-NC-SA-4.0`

Key effect: **the documentation may be shared and adapted for non-commercial
purposes only, with attribution to `warterbili`, and derivative works must
carry the same CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license**. Commercial use of any kind
(including republication on a paid platform, integration into a commercial
training corpus, or use as marketing material for a commercial anti-bot
service) is **not permitted**.

## Why a Dual Track

The Creative Commons FAQ explicitly recommends against using CC for software
because CC was not designed to handle distribution-and-modification
mechanics specific to source code. The Free Software Foundation similarly
recommends against using GPL/AGPL for prose documentation.

Combining the two:

- **AGPL-3.0** protects against closed-source SaaS exploitation of the
  reverse-engineering code while still permitting personal use, research,
  and contribution back.
- **CC BY-NC-SA 4.0** explicitly forbids commercial use of the methodology
  and findings, making the documentation unusable for commercial anti-bot
  bypass services without permission from the author.

Together they form a two-layer anti-abuse shield.

## Disclaimer (Restated From README §16)

This project is released strictly for **research, education, and personal
security-audit purposes**. The author (`warterbili`) accepts no liability for
any direct or indirect damage caused by any party's use of this project.
Users must comply with the laws of their jurisdiction (US CFAA, EU GDPR,
China Cybersecurity / Data Security / PIPL, etc.) and the terms of service
of any third-party platform they interact with. The project does NOT target
any specific merchant; iFood and Grubhub serve only as technical objects of
protocol-level reverse-engineering research.

Use of this project — whether the code under AGPL-3.0 or the documentation
under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 — implies acceptance of the disclaimer in README §16.

## Responsible Disclosure

If PerimeterX / HUMAN Security wishes to initiate coordinated disclosure,
the author reserves the right to adjust the disclosure scope within 90 days
of a formal request. Contact via GitHub Issues.

